\title{\textbf{The Coverage Wall and the Verification Tax}\\[2pt]
\normalsize A sharp phase transition and design law for the RLVR policy--vs--verifier game}
\author{Guangyu Wang\\ \texttt{billgywang@gmail.com}\\[4pt]
\small An application of the core theory \emph{The Wall, the Game, and the Cliff Criterion} to RLVR verification (transplanted by isomorphism; Stage-A verified)}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Reinforcement learning from verifiable rewards (RLVR) replaces human labels with executable
verifiers---answer checkers, schema validators, unit-test harnesses. Under optimization pressure the
policy learns to satisfy the verifier while failing the task: \emph{verifier false positives become
rewardable}. We characterize when this must happen in three acts, \emph{proved by an explicit isomorphism}
(Lemma~\ref{l:iso}) to the core theory paper---whose high-dimensional threshold,
information-theoretic converse, game value, and adaptive-collapse law are theorems at stated rigor---and
\emph{verified here in Stage-A} in coverage notation (\S\ref{sec:stageA}). \emph{(i) Mechanism:} against a \emph{fixed} verifier, the extractable
information about wrong-vs-right collapses at a critical coverage $m^\star$ (pressure
$\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}=1-\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}/s^2$), with a matching converse---\emph{no} test of
the $K$ checked evaluations detects the defect---so verification fails as a \emph{cliff}, not a
slope. \emph{(ii) Game value:} when the policy chooses how to spread the defect, the wall becomes a
critical \emph{exploit value} $V^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$; spreading over the correctness subspace buys a
factor that a smarter verifier claws back, and that \emph{saturates} once the defect's total checked
variance gives it away. \emph{(iii) Design law:} the defect's footprint in the reward-relevant
subspace is \emph{irreducible}---the policy can move it into the verifier's false-positive region but
not erase it while still collecting reward---so an \emph{adaptive} verifier that aims checks at the
(public) reward criteria and spends its evaluation budget \emph{collapses} the wall. Robust
verification is therefore not a better checker but \emph{which checks you add}. The covering
regime---correctness richer than test coverage---is the RLVR default; the core characterizes its
canonical (concentrated-direction) model as a \emph{slope} (detection linear in the coverage fraction
$\meff/K_c$), leaving the exact covering law open.
\end{abstract}

\section{Problem, thesis, and the picture}
RLVR trains policies against executable verifiers. Optimization pressure elicits \emph{verifier
hacking}: the policy makes the checks pass while the task is wrong (Helff et al.\ 2604.15149; Ray et
al.\ 2606.01066; Khalifa et al.\ 2603.07084). Prior work supplies pieces but not the transition: a
per-solution detection-\emph{saturation} bound $1-(1-\bar p)^{n^\star_{\mathrm{eff}}}$ (SAGA
2507.06920); an \emph{economic inevitability} result with a conjectured capability threshold
(2603.28063); an \emph{empirical complexity threshold}---hacking emerges when the exploit is simpler
than the honest solution (2605.02964); and software-engineering \emph{undecidability} (Howden 76;
Weyuker 86). What is missing is a \emph{sharp high-dimensional phase transition}: a critical verifier
coverage $m^\star$ past which the verifier's information about wrong-vs-right collapses, and the price
of staying above it.

\paragraph{The picture (transplanted from the core).} We reject the fatalistic reading
(``verifiers are gameable, RLVR is doomed''). A wrong completion leaves a \emph{statistical defect
footprint} in the reward-relevant subspace of the task. The policy can \emph{relocate} that footprint
into directions the verifier does not check---its \emph{false-positive region}---but, because the
footprint \emph{is} the reward-directed deviation, it cannot \emph{erase} it while still collecting
reward. Whether verification survives optimization pressure is therefore not a fixed fact but the
value of a game over \emph{which checks the verifier runs}, set by three levers: coverage $\gamma$,
evaluation budget $\kappa$, and---decisively---whether the checks can \emph{aim} at the reward
criteria. The wall is real and sharp against a fixed verifier; it rises, and can collapse, as the
verifier gains these. The crucial RLVR twist: the reward criteria are \emph{public} (the verifier
defines pass/fail), so aiming is available in principle---yet real test suites cover far fewer
dimensions than correctness has, which is exactly the covering regime---characterized in the core as a slope---where the wall persists.

\paragraph{Machine map.} Monitoring wall $\to$ \textbf{coverage wall}; null-channel dimension
$k_{\mathrm{null}}\to$ \textbf{false-positive-region dimension} $\kfp=D-\meff$; monitorability tax
$\to$ \textbf{verification tax} $\lcov$; monitor resolution $\alpha\to$ \textbf{coverage}
$\gamma=\meff/D$; data budget $n/d\to$ \textbf{verifier power} $\kappa=K/D$; model-vs-monitor $\to$
\textbf{policy-vs-verifier}. The transplant is near-verbatim; the core paper proves and verifies the
identical machine numerically, which is the speed and credibility argument.

\section{The Coverage Channel (Stage-A toy model)}
Task feature space $\R^D$ ($D$ = task intrinsic dimension). A wrong completion injects a
\emph{defect of blatancy $s^2$} along a unit direction $v\in\R^D$ (small $s$ = subtle error). The
verifier resolves only a subspace $\Sver$ of \emph{effective dimension} $\meff$ (its \emph{independent}
checks) and accumulates evidence over $K$ evaluation instances, observing the deviation through a
random design $\Phi\in\R^{\meff\times K}$ and deciding defect vs.\ clean. Under \emph{optimization
pressure} $\rho\in[0,1]$ the policy steers a fraction $\rho$ of the defect energy into the verifier
null space $\Sver^\perp$ of dimension $\kfp=D-\meff$; the \emph{checked} defect is $s^2(1-\rho)$.

\emph{Order parameters:} coverage $\gamma=\meff/D$ (\,$\leftrightarrow\alpha$\,); verifier power
$\kappa=K/D$ (\,$\leftrightarrow n/d$\,); blatancy $s^2$; pressure $\rho$; check correlation
$\bar\rho_{\mathrm{check}}$ with $\meff=m(1-\bar\rho_{\mathrm{check}})$ (the SAGA effective-count
hook). Detection is spiked/planted recovery through the design with \textbf{bulk edge}
$\sqrt{\meff/K}=\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$.

\begin{remark}[Key modeling choice --- two knobs, kept separate]
Naïve ``more checks'' is \emph{non-monotone}: more checks shrink the null space but raise the
estimation-noise floor. \textbf{Coverage $\gamma$} shrinks the hiding space $\kfp$; \textbf{power
$\kappa$} (instance budget) beats the detection edge. The clean threshold lives in their interplay,
and the game (Acts~II--III) is played on both.
\end{remark}

\section{The transplant: a reusable isomorphism}\label{sec:iso}
The results below are not re-derived; they are transported from the core by a single explicit
map. We isolate that map here as a self-contained lemma so it can be cited on its own---by this
paper, and by a future unified treatment for which it is the shared object.

\begin{lemma}[Coverage--core isomorphism]\label{l:iso}
The Stage-A Coverage Channel is the partial-channel model of the core theory paper under the relabeling
\[
\begin{aligned}
&v\ (\text{defect dir.})\leftrightarrow u,\quad
\meff\ (\text{eff.\ checks})\leftrightarrow \dmon,\quad
K\ (\text{evaluations})\leftrightarrow n,\\[2pt]
&\gamma{=}\meff/D\ (\text{coverage})\leftrightarrow \alpha,\quad
\kappa{=}K/D\ (\text{power})\leftrightarrow n/d,\quad
(\Sver^{\perp},\kfp)\ (\text{FP region})\leftrightarrow (\Smon^{\perp},\knull),
\end{aligned}
\]
under which the effective aspect ratio maps exactly, $\gamma/\kappa=\meff/K\leftrightarrow\dmon/n$, and
the detection edge maps to $\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}\leftrightarrow\sqrt{\dmon/n}$. Recovering the defect
direction $v$ from the $K$ checked deviations is \emph{verbatim} the planted-vector / spiked-covariance
problem of the core. Consequently every result there transfers as a proved statement here,
at the same rigor tier: the wall and its converse and price are unconditional; the game value is a
theorem under the (relabeled) low-rank, fixed-coverage assumptions A1--A4; the saturation is a scaling
bound; and the adaptive collapse is conditional on the (relabeled) public-and-coverable assumptions
B1--B4. Below we state each and confirm it numerically in coverage notation (\S\ref{sec:stageA}).
\end{lemma}

\noindent The remainder of Act~I is the core's Props.~1--4 and its effective-rank corollary,
read through Lemma~\ref{l:iso}.

\begin{remark}[The isomorphism is a shared asset]
Lemma~\ref{l:iso} belongs to neither game in particular: it identifies both as instances of recovering
a planted signal through a partially observed channel, with the same effective aspect ratio and the
same BBP edge. We keep the full statement here (where it does concrete work), written so a future
core paper carries it as its shared object; monitoring is the $(\alpha,n/d)$ instance,
coverage the $(\gamma,\kappa)$ instance, and the covering game of Act~III is the one regime where the
two instances still diverge in difficulty.
\end{remark}

\section*{Act I --- the mechanism: a sharp, information-theoretic wall}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Act I}

\begin{proposition}[Coverage wall / phase transition]\label{t:wall}
In the proportional regime $D,\meff,K\to\infty$, $\meff/D\to\gamma$, $K/D\to\kappa$, the verifier's
defect-recovery overlap $\langle\hat v,v\rangle^2$ is strictly positive for $\rho<\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$
and \emph{exactly zero} for $\rho>\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$, with the closed form
\begin{equation}\label{eq:covwall}
\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}} \;=\; \Big[\,1-\frac{\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}}{s^2}\,\Big]_0^1
\;=\; \Big[\,1-\frac{\sqrt{(\meff/D)/(K/D)}}{s^2}\,\Big]_0^1 .
\end{equation}
Equivalently, at the policy's evasion optimum the false-positive region has positive measure and is
reachable in $O(1)$ reward queries iff effective coverage falls below a critical $m^\star=\gamma^\star
D$ ($\gamma^\star$ fixed by the CGMT fixed point at $(\kappa,s)$). Correlated checks inflate the
nominal count, $m^\star_{\mathrm{nominal}}=m^\star/(1-\bar\rho_{\mathrm{check}})$. It is a cliff, not a
slope, and it sharpens with $D$. As in the core, the formula is \emph{clipped}: when
$s^2\le\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$ the checked defect is already below the edge and the verifier is
\emph{blind at start} ($\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}{=}0$); when $s^2\gg\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$ the wall
sits near $1$.
\end{proposition}

\noindent\emph{Proof.} By Lemma~\ref{l:iso} this is the core's wall (core Prop.~1 and its
BBP overlap law) under the relabeling, with edge $\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$; the clipping and the three
regimes are the core's regime table read through the map. Verified in coverage notation in
Fig.~\ref{fig:covA}a,b. \hfill$\square$

\begin{corollary}[Effective coverage: correlated/low-rank checks raise the wall]\label{t:reff}
The ambient $D$ cancels in $\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$; what enters is $\gamma/\kappa=\meff/K$. For a
verifier whose checks are correlated or whose resolvable check-covariance $\Sigma_{\mathrm{ver}}$ is
low-rank, $\meff$ is replaced by its stable rank $m_{\mathrm{eff}}^{\mathrm{stab}}=
\operatorname{tr}\Sigma_{\mathrm{ver}}/\|\Sigma_{\mathrm{ver}}\|\le\meff$ (the SAGA effective-count
$\meff=m(1-\bar\rho_{\mathrm{check}})$ is the flat special case, which is exact). Since a smaller
effective coverage \emph{lowers} the edge and \emph{raises} $\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$, correlated
checks make the defect \emph{easier} to force below the wall---the practically relevant direction, and
the coverage reading of the core's Cor.~1 (exact for flat/whitened checks, a deformed-MP proxy in
general).
\end{corollary}

\begin{proposition}[A basic limit, not one estimator (converse)]\label{t:converse}
Below the wall ($s^2(1-\rho)<\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$) the checked-deviation laws of wrong and clean
completions are mutually contiguous: a Le~Cam second-moment bound gives
$\E_0[L_K^2]\to(1-\beta^2/(\gamma/\kappa))^{-1/2}<\infty$, so \emph{no} test of the $K$ checked
evaluations---regardless of decision rule or compute---detects the defect consistently. The detection
threshold coincides with the recovery threshold; the coverage wall is information-theoretic, not an
artifact of a particular verifier. \emph{This closes ``just build a smarter checker.''}
\end{proposition}

\noindent\emph{Proof.} The core's converse (core Prop.~2, Le~Cam second moment) under Lemma~\ref{l:iso}, with
$\gamma\mapsto\gamma/\kappa$; verified in Fig.~\ref{fig:covA}b. \hfill$\square$

\begin{proposition}[The price of coverage: growing floor, feasibility ceiling, triple coincidence]\label{t:tax}
To keep hackability below $\tau$ against defects of blatancy $s$ while the policy optimizes
($\rho\to\rho_{\max}$), the retained \emph{checked-defect fraction} is bounded below,
$1-\rho_{\max}\ge\beta(\tau)/s^2$, whose floor \emph{grows} as $s\to0$ or the effective coverage
$\gamma/\kappa$ falls; since the fraction is $\le1$, this is a \emph{feasibility ceiling}: once the
floor exceeds $1$ (equivalently $\kappa<c(\tau)\gamma/s^4$, i.e.\ instance budget $K<c(\tau)D\gamma/s^4$,
or $\meff<m^\star(\tau)$), \emph{no} operating point keeps hackability below $\tau$ and the verifier is
defeated outright. Under a positive-slope assumption (throughput / eval-cost loss rising with mandated
coverage) the verification tax $\lcov$ grows with the floor---the sharp form of ``harder tasks $+$ more
inference compute $\to$ more hacking''---and beyond the ceiling no evaluation budget buys target-level
verification. At $m^\star$ three events coincide: the wall, the divergence of the verification shadow
price, and the defect energy crossing entirely into the verifier null space---one order parameter
$\beta_{\mathrm{sig}}\to0$, three readouts.
\end{proposition}

\noindent\emph{Proof.} The core's Prop.~3 (energy floor, rigorous) and Prop.~4 (triple
coincidence) under Lemma~\ref{l:iso}; the feasibility-ceiling reading is the core's bounded-fraction
correction, and the slope $\kappa_{\mathrm{tax}}$ is task-calibrated (Stage~A.5). The wall location that sets the
floor is verified in Fig.~\ref{fig:covA}a,b. \hfill$\square$

\section*{Act II --- the wall's height is a game value}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Act II}
So far the defect direction $v$ and the pressure $\rho$ are exogenous. In reality the policy
\emph{chooses} how to spread the defect across the reward-relevant subspace to minimize detectability
while remaining a successful exploit (delivering exploit value $V$), and the verifier chooses which
subspace to check. The wall becomes the value of this game---a critical \emph{exploit value}
$V^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$, not an imposed pressure.

\begin{proposition}[Endogenous defect spectrum]\label{t:game}
Let the reward-relevant (correctness) subspace have dimension $K_c$ and value density $g$, and let the
verifier have fixed coverage edge $\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$. The min--max equilibrium spreads the defect
\emph{flatly} over the $K_c$ correctness directions (each sub-critical). The exploit is undetectable
iff the delivered exploit value is below a critical value:
\[
\text{coverage (peak) verifier:}\quad V<V^\star_{\mathrm{peak}}=gK_c\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa};
\qquad
\text{optimal verifier:}\quad V<V^\star_{\mathrm{opt}}=g\sqrt{K_c\,\gamma/\kappa}.
\]
Thus $\rho$ is endogenous; correctness rank $K_c$ is the policy's resource (spreading the defect keeps
each check sub-threshold), worth a factor $K_c$ against a peak verifier but only $\sqrt{K_c}$ against
the optimal one---the \emph{verifier-sophistication gap} is exactly $\sqrt{K_c}$. ($K_c=1$ recovers
Prop.~\ref{t:wall}.) This holds under the (relabeled) assumptions A1--A4: orthogonal defect
directions, fixed coverage aimed to contain the correctness subspace ($K_c\le\meff$), sub-extensive
$K_c=o(D)$, and a second-order (aggregate-residual) signature.
\end{proposition}

\noindent\emph{Proof.} The core's game-value theorem (core Prop.~5, proved under A1--A4; optimal
branch via the multi-spike second moment of its App.~C) under Lemma~\ref{l:iso}, with edge
$\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$ and $g$ the correctness value density. Verified in Fig.~\ref{fig:covA}c. \hfill$\square$

\begin{proposition}[Spreading self-defeats: the $\sqrt{K_c}$ advantage saturates]\label{t:sat}
An extensive defect ($K_c=\Theta(D)$) raises the \emph{total checked residual variance} by an
extensive amount, which the trivial aggregate-coverage statistic
$\widehat T=\tfrac1K\sum_i\|\Phi\,\text{residual}_i\|^2$ resolves. Hence the hideable exploit value is
capped independently of $K_c$,
$V^\star_{\mathrm{ext}}=\Theta\!\big(g/\sqrt{\gamma\kappa}\big)$, and the $\sqrt{K_c}$ growth saturates
at correctness rank $K_c^\star=\Theta(1/\gamma^2)$: beyond it, spreading the defect wider only exposes
more total residual. The exact optimal-verifier value is the free multiplicative convolution of the
Marchenko--Pastur bulk with the checked defect spectrum, \emph{sandwiched} between the peak (spike)
bound and the trace (aggregate) bound.
\end{proposition}

\noindent\emph{Proof (scaling).} The core's saturation proposition (core Prop.~6) under
Lemma~\ref{l:iso}: the extensive defect raises the total checked residual, resolved by the aggregate
statistic once it clears its noise floor $\propto\sqrt{1/(\gamma\kappa)}$; the cap
$V^\star_{\mathrm{ext}}=\Theta(g/\sqrt{\gamma\kappa})$ is $K_c$-independent, and the exact
optimal value is the free-convolution edge, sandwiched as stated. \hfill$\square$

\section*{Act III --- the design law: aiming is decisive}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Act III}

\begin{proposition}[Adaptive coverage collapses the wall]\label{t:adapt}
The RLVR twist: the reward criteria are \emph{public}---the verifier defines pass/fail, so it
\emph{knows} the reward-relevant subspace. Let the verifier \emph{adapt} its checks, aiming coverage
wherever it chooses. When the correctness subspace fits the coverage budget ($K_c\le\meff$), the
verifier aims at it and measures the \emph{total} reward-relevant residual. Delivering exploit value
$V$ forces reward-relevant residual $\propto V/g$---exactly what an aiming coverage test measures---so
\emph{no defect spectrum escapes} (the test is spread-invariant), and the hideable exploit value
collapses to $V^\star_{\mathrm{adapt}}=\Theta(g\sqrt{K_c/K})\to0$ as the evaluation budget $K$ grows.
The spreading advantage of Props.~\ref{t:game}--\ref{t:sat} \emph{evaporates}: what the policy hides
from a fixed test suite, an aiming verifier catches. The coverage wall protects the exploiter only
against a verifier that cannot aim its checks or is starved of evaluation budget. Assumptions
(relabeled B1--B4): the reward criteria (hence the correctness subspace) are public; the verifier may
re-aim its coverage and $K_c\le\meff$; it uses the total reward-relevant residual (aggregate) test;
and exploit value is delivered as reward-relevant residual, so it is forced and irreducible.
\end{proposition}

\noindent\emph{Proof.} The core's adaptive-collapse proposition (core Prop.~7, conditional on
B1--B4) under Lemma~\ref{l:iso}; $V^\star_{\mathrm{adapt}}=\Theta(g\sqrt{K_c/K})\to0$ as the
evaluation budget $K$ grows. Verified in Fig.~\ref{fig:covA}d. \hfill$\square$

\begin{center}
\fbox{\begin{minipage}{0.94\linewidth}
\textbf{Box 1: design law for robust verifiers.} The analysis is prescriptive, not fatalistic---it
says how to keep the coverage wall high.
\begin{itemize}\setlength{\itemsep}{1pt}
\item \emph{Aim checks at the reward criteria.} The defect footprint lives where reward is
collected---and the verifier \emph{defines} that (pass/fail is public). Cover those dimensions first
(Prop.~\ref{t:adapt}); aiming beats any fixed generic test suite.
\item \emph{Match coverage to correctness rank.} Keep $\meff\ge K_c$ so the correctness subspace fits;
below that, the covering game leaves exploitable gaps.
\item \emph{Spend the evaluation budget.} Wall height scales as $\sqrt{1/K}$: more evaluation
instances drive $V^\star\to0$.
\item \emph{Use aggregate (second-order) coverage statistics}, not per-check pass rates: the sharp
wall is a covariance-spike phenomenon; per-check pass/fail is the smooth (thresholdless) case.
\item \emph{Add the most decorrelated check next} (\texttt{next\_check}); read the wall height with the
Coverage Meter and \emph{harden before the wall}---pass rates give no warning before the collapse.
\end{itemize}
\end{minipage}}
\end{center}

\begin{remark}[The covering regime is a slope (per the core), and it is the RLVR default]
Prop.~\ref{t:adapt} closes the game whenever coverage can span correctness ($K_c\le\meff$). The
complement, $K_c>\meff$---correctness \emph{richer than test coverage}---is the practically dominant
regime: unit tests never span all correctness dimensions of a program, the verifier checks an
$\meff/K_c$ fraction, and the policy hides the exploit in the unchecked directions. The core
characterizes the canonical (concentrated-direction) version of this covering game as a \emph{slope},
not a sharp threshold: forced randomization makes detection linear in the coverage fraction,
$p_{\mathrm{det}}=\meff/K_c$. So this is \emph{not} a warning-free collapse but a smooth, \emph{priced}
degradation whose steepness is the coverage-to-correctness ratio; the full game and its exact covering
law are the one piece left open. Unlike monitoring, where an adaptive monitor may simply win, in RLVR
this covering slope is the \emph{default}: correctness routinely outruns coverage, which is why the
coverage wall---and the discipline of aiming and spending budget to keep $\meff$ track $K_c$---matters in
practice.
\end{remark}

\section{CGMT auxiliary-problem sketch (the shared machine)}
Recovering $v$ from the checked deviation is the spiked-covariance / planted-vector problem, a min--max
with Gaussian design $G\in\R^{\meff\times K}$:
\[
\Phi(G)=\min_{\|w\|=1}\max_{\|q\|\le1}\ q^\top(G/\sqrt K)w+\psi\big(w,q;\,s\sqrt{1-\rho}\big).
\]
CGMT reduces this to an auxiliary problem $\phi(g,h)=\min_w\max_q\|q\|\,g^\top w+\|w\|\,h^\top q+\psi$,
scalarized to a $2$--$3$-dimensional fixed point. The signal order parameter $\beta_{\mathrm{sig}}$
(the $v$-overlap) is $0$ precisely when $s^2(1-\rho)<\sqrt{\meff/K}$, giving $\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$
and the sharpness of Prop.~\ref{t:wall}; differentiating the value function in the detectability
constraint yields the tax floor of Prop.~\ref{t:tax}; a second replica gives the converse
(Prop.~\ref{t:converse}). This is structurally identical to the core's CGMT sketch---the transplant
is near-verbatim, and the core paper has proved and verified the identical fixed point, converse, game value,
and adaptive-collapse law in simulation.

\section{Stage-A numerical validation (coverage notation)}\label{sec:stageA}
We re-run the core's Stage-A protocol in coverage notation (\texttt{numpy}, CPU), i.e.\ recover a
planted defect $v$ from $K$ checked deviations at coverage $\gamma$ and power $\kappa$, edge
$\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$; blatancy $s^2{=}1.414$ so $\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}{=}0.5$ at
$\gamma{=}0.5,\kappa{=}1$. All numbers below are produced by this re-parametrization
(\texttt{coverage\_stageA.py}); none are hand-set.

\begin{figure}[h]\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{coverage_stageA.png}
\caption{\textbf{Coverage wall, Stage A.} (a) Defect-detection AUC vs pressure $\rho$: the collapse at
$\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}{=}0.5$ sharpens with task dimension $D\in\{100,300,900\}$---a true
transition, not a finite-size slope. (b) A weaker verifier (smaller power $\kappa$) is blinded at
lower pressure: $\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$ moves to $0.29,0.50,0.65$ for $\kappa\in\{0.5,1,2\}$,
matching~\eqref{eq:covwall}. (c) Game value: the measured critical exploit value grows as
$gK_c\sqrt{\gamma/\kappa}$ against a peak (coverage) verifier but only $g\sqrt{K_c\gamma/\kappa}$
against an aggregate one---the $\sqrt{K_c}$ gap (Prop.~\ref{t:game}); the aggregate statistic is a
practical proxy realizing part of it, so the measured gap is a conservative lower bound. (d) Adaptive
collapse: fully spread over the correctness subspace, a fixed test suite is blind (AUC $\approx0.5$),
but an aiming verifier that measures the total reward-relevant residual catches the exploit
(AUC $\to0.93$)---spreading is useless against it (Prop.~\ref{t:adapt}).}
\label{fig:covA}
\end{figure}

The four core claims hold on the coverage channel exactly as the isomorphism (Lemma~\ref{l:iso})
predicts: the wall location matches~\eqref{eq:covwall} and sharpens with $D$; it moves with verifier
power $\kappa$; the game value shows the $\sqrt{K_c}$ sophistication gap; and an aiming verifier
collapses the wall that a fixed suite cannot see. This is the ``identical machine, verified'' argument
made concrete in RLVR notation; the tax slope and a real toy verifier are Stage~A.5.

\section{Instrument: the Coverage Meter (interface)}
A verifier-side diagnostic; \texttt{next\_check} is the verifier's \emph{game action} (Act~III), not a
utility.
\begin{itemize}\setlength{\itemsep}{1pt}
\item \texttt{fp\_region\_dim(task\_geom, verifier\_op)}$\to\kfp=D-\meff$: participation ratio of the
deviation covariance outside the checks' resolvable operator (mirrors \texttt{null\_channel\_dim}).
\item \texttt{coverage\_wall\_estimate(s\_hat, gamma, kappa)}$\to\hat\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$ with a
bootstrap band; flags when the operating point is within $\delta$ of the wall.
\item \texttt{verification\_price(completions, labels)}$\to\hat\lcov$: marginal task/throughput cost per
unit preserved detection information, bootstrap CI.
\item \texttt{next\_check(verifier, task\_geom)}$\to$ the maximally FP-region-shrinking (most
decorrelated) check to add---the verifier's best-response move; grounds the empirical hardening
ablations of 2606.01066.
\item \texttt{StoppingRule}: halt RLVR / flag the verifier when $\hat\rho\to\hat\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$
or $\hat\lcov$ spikes---``harden before the wall.''
\end{itemize}

\section{Stage plan (evidence hierarchy)}
\emph{Stage A (done; \S\ref{sec:stageA}, Fig.~\ref{fig:covA}).} Synthetic Coverage Channel with
controlled $(D,\meff,K,s)$: confirmed that (a) defect-detection AUC collapses $1.0\to0.5$ across
$\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$ and sharpens with $D$; (b) the wall moves with verifier power $\kappa$ as
the closed form predicts; (c) the game value shows the $\sqrt{K_c}$ gap; and (d) an aiming verifier
collapses the wall a fixed suite cannot see. \emph{(This is the re-parametrization of the identical
core simulations, now reproduced in coverage notation.)} \emph{Stage A.5 (next).} A real
toy verifier (math final-answer / JSON-schema / toy unit tests) $+$ a tiny REINFORCE policy: exploit
onset must land at the predicted $m^\star$, and \texttt{next\_check} must pre-empt it; this stage
also calibrates the one free tax slope. Keep claims qualitative. \emph{Stage B (specified; GPU).}
Real
RLVR agentic coding under a real test-suite verifier; falsification: the wall must appear where
$(D-\meff)/\kappa$ predicts, and the tax must scale with defect subtlety / task dimension. Ground-truth
datasets: Terminal-wrench (2604.17596), ImpossibleBench (2510.20270), Countdown-Code (2603.07084).

\section{What this is, and is not}
This is a \emph{characterization} sister paper: the load-bearing results---a phase transition, an
information-theoretic converse, a game value, and an adaptive-collapse design law---are \emph{proved
here by isomorphism} (Lemma~\ref{l:iso}) to the core's theorems and \emph{verified in Stage-A}
(\S\ref{sec:stageA}), inheriting the core's rigor tiers (wall/converse/price unconditional; game
value under A1--A4; saturation a scaling bound; adaptive collapse conditional on B1--B4). \emph{Validation
on a real RLVR verifier requires Stage~B}---no real verifier has been used yet. For self-containedness,
Appendix~\ref{app:selfcontained} restates the wall and converse and proves them in coverage notation
from the CGMT fixed point, so this paper's central claim stands without the core. Sold \emph{strictly} as: a sharp coverage
threshold $m^\star$; a verification-tax divergence; a game value with a saturating spreading advantage;
a design law (aiming collapses the wall) with a Meter that reads the wall height and prices the next
check; and closed-form prediction of the empirical hardening curves. \textbf{Not} ``verifiers can be
gamed'' (taken: 2604.15149, 2606.01066); \textbf{not} ``finite evaluation $\to$ inevitable distortion''
(taken: 2603.28063, Holmström--Milgrom 91); \textbf{not} detection tooling (taken: IPT, fuzzing,
gradient fingerprints). The novelty is \emph{when} optimization must reach the false-positive region,
\emph{what} coverage costs, and \emph{what a verifier must do} to keep the wall high.

\appendix
\section{Self-contained core: the coverage wall, proved in coverage notation}\label{app:selfcontained}
The main text transports its results from the core by Lemma~\ref{l:iso}. For self-containedness
we restate the load-bearing result---the wall and its converse---and give a proof in coverage notation
that does \emph{not} depend on the core being read. (It is the same CGMT fixed point; we keep it
here so this paper's central claim stands alone.)

\paragraph{Setup, recalled.} A wrong completion plants a defect of blatancy $s^2$ along a unit
direction $v\in\R^{D}$. The verifier resolves a subspace $\Sver$ of effective dimension $\meff$ and
accumulates $K$ evaluations, observing the deviation through an i.i.d.\ Gaussian design
$G\in\R^{\meff\times K}$. Under pressure $\rho$ the policy routes a fraction $\rho$ of the defect into
$\Sver^{\perp}$, leaving a checked defect $\beta=s^2(1-\rho)$ along the visible component
$\tilde v$. Write the effective aspect ratio $\Gamma\equiv\gamma/\kappa=\meff/K$; the edge is
$\sqrt\Gamma$.

\begin{theorem}[Coverage wall + converse, self-contained]\label{th:selfwall}
In the proportional regime $\meff,K\to\infty$ with $\meff/K\to\Gamma$:
\emph{(i, recovery)} the verifier's defect-recovery overlap $\langle\hat v,v\rangle^2$ is
$\big[(1-\Gamma/\beta^2)/(1+\Gamma/\beta)\big]_+$, strictly positive for $\beta>\sqrt\Gamma$ and
exactly zero for $\beta\le\sqrt\Gamma$, i.e.\ zero iff
$\rho\ge\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}=\big[1-\sqrt\Gamma/s^2\big]_0^1$;
\emph{(ii, converse)} for $\beta<\sqrt\Gamma$ the checked-deviation laws of wrong and clean
completions are contiguous---the Bayesian likelihood-ratio second moment
$\E_0[L_K^2]\to(1-\beta^2/\Gamma)^{-1/2}<\infty$---so no test of the $K$ checked evaluations detects
the defect consistently. The two thresholds coincide at $\beta=\sqrt\Gamma$.
\end{theorem}

\paragraph{Proof (CGMT fixed point, coverage notation).} Recovering $v$ is the planted-vector problem
$\Phi=\max_{\|w\|=1}\max_{\|q\|\le1}\tfrac1{\sqrt K}\big[w^\top G q+\sqrt\beta\,(w^\top\tilde
v)(\eta^\top q)\big]$ with $\eta\in\R^{K}$ the planted loading. By the Convex Gaussian Min-max
(Gordon) substitution the bilinear term $w^\top Gq$ is replaced by $\|q\|\,g^\top w+\|w\|\,h^\top q$
($g\in\R^{\meff},h\in\R^{K}$ standard Gaussian), and scalarizing in the overlap
$\mu=\langle w,\tilde v\rangle$ (optimizing the nuisance directions and using $\meff/K\to\Gamma$)
reduces the auxiliary problem to the one-dimensional potential
\[
\Phi_{\mathrm{AO}}(\mu)=\sqrt{\Gamma(1-\mu^2)}+\sqrt{1+\beta\mu^2}
=(\sqrt\Gamma+1)+\tfrac{\mu^2}{2}(\beta-\sqrt\Gamma)+O(\mu^4).
\]
Hence $\mu=0$ is the unique maximizer when $\beta<\sqrt\Gamma$, and a nontrivial branch bifurcates
(pitchfork) when $\beta>\sqrt\Gamma$; solving $\Phi_{\mathrm{AO}}'(\mu)=0$ gives the overlap
$\mu^{\star2}=(\beta^2-\Gamma)/(\beta(\beta+\Gamma))$, which equals the BBP/Paul eigenvector overlap of
(i). Thus the signal overlap is $0$ iff $\beta\le\sqrt\Gamma$, i.e.\ $s^2(1-\rho)\le\sqrt{\meff/K}$,
i.e.\ $\rho\ge\rho^\star_{\mathrm{cov}}$---continuous in $\mu$ but non-analytic in $\rho$ (the
sharpness). For (ii), the single-planted-direction Le~Cam second moment with a uniform prior on $v$ is
$\E_0[L_K^2]\to(1-\beta^2/\Gamma)^{-1/2}$, finite iff $\beta<\sqrt\Gamma$; a bounded second moment
gives contiguity, hence no consistent test. Consistency checks: the $\mu{=}0$ potential value
$1+\sqrt\Gamma$ matches the Marchenko--Pastur edge, and the overlap matches BBP; both agree with the
Stage-A simulation of \S\ref{sec:stageA}. \hfill$\square$

\paragraph{Scope of this appendix.} This restates the wall and converse only---the two statements this
paper most depends on---so the central claim is self-contained. The game value
(Prop.~\ref{t:game}), saturation (Prop.~\ref{t:sat}), and adaptive collapse (Prop.~\ref{t:adapt})
transfer by the same fixed point under Lemma~\ref{l:iso}; their full proofs are in the core (or a
future core), and their Stage-A confirmations are in \S\ref{sec:stageA}. We present the CGMT reduction
at the level of the standard Gordon substitution, not a self-contained regularity proof; its validity
rests on the standard CGMT hypotheses plus the consistency checks and simulation above.

